description: From Middle English squaimous, queimous, swaymos, sweymows, partly from Anglo-Norman escoimus, escoymous, of unknown origin (possibly from the English); and partly from Middle English sweme, sweyme, swayme, sqweme (“sorrow, grief, unconsciousness, dizzy spell, faintness”)  +‎ -ous. See sweam and sweem.

adjectives.description: squeamous (comparative more squeamous, superlative most squeamous)
